symptoms: A lump near the anus, which may be sensitive or painful
Areas of dark or light skin
Bleeding under the skin, nose, or gums
Blood on toilet paper or in the toilet after a bowel movement
Bone fractures that occur more easily than expected
Bone spurs (bony growths around the joint)
Burning abdominal pain, especially between meals or at night
Coughing, especially at night or early morning
Decreased mobility due to limb enlargement
Difficulty sleeping due to coughing or wheezing
Double vision in a single eye
Dry, cracked skin that may bleed
Dry, red, or silvery patches on the scalp, elbows, knees, or lower back
Fluid-filled blisters that eventually crust over
Formation of uric acid crystals under the skin
Frequent prescription changes for glasses or contact lenses
Grating sensation when moving the joint
Itching or irritation in the anal area
Joint stiffness, especially in the morning
Joint swelling (less common than in rheumatoid arthritis)
Limited range of motion in the joint
Lingering discomfort after the acute pain subsides
Lymph nodes may become swollen and painful
Nail changes, including pitting, discoloration, and separation from the nailbed
Numbness or loss of sensation in affected areas
Pain or burning sensation during urination
Pain or discomfort during bowel movements
Pain, swelling, and tenderness in the limbs
Painful or tender lump(s) near the anus
Pounding in the chest, neck, or ears
Raw, sensitive, or swollen skin from scratching
Red patches of skin covered with silvery scales
Redness and warmth around the affected joint
Sensation of a lump in the throat
Severe, throbbing headache, usually on one side of the head
Swelling in ankles, feet, or legs
Tingling or numbness in face or extremities
Tingling or numbness in hands or feet
Tingling or prickling sensation at the site of the bite
Ulcers on the soles of the feet
